        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Yes, I agree.  I think having some sanity checking is OK.  But I do not think GMT can run _gmt_set_dataset_minmax_ on the users externally passed-in memory since it would make changes.  So the way to do this is for GMT to report that the external container is flawed and print error messages.  This will presumably only be seen by external developers who then will fix their code.\r\n\r\nRe you question: You may correctly have set n_rows for segment 1 in your input, but you did not update the dataset's n_records variable, which still is 0, and pslegend checks that to see how much to allocate, and you your case that is 0, hence the crash.",
